     You are now entering the newbie quest tutorial area.  This place was
specially designed to teach you about quests, both the idea behind
them and ways to solve them.  If you are familiar with quests and
MUDs in general, you'll probably find the approach taken herein to
be ridiculously pedantic and entirely extraneous, but then again,
this wasn't designed for you.  This is for the completely clueless,
those who have no idea what a quest is, let alone how to do one
or even why anyone would want to do one.  This place is designed
for people like me (Lingo) when I started.
     First off, a quest is a task set forth by the builders on Darkwind
to test your mettle, both the physical stuff of which your character
here is made and that brain of yours.  Some lean towards more
of one aspect than the other, but almost all have at least some
of both.  You can find out which aspect is emphasized in a particular
quest by going to the adventurer's guild (1 west, 1 south of where
you logged in) and typing 'list' then selecting one of the quests
listed and typing 'list <quest_name>'.  This will yield a short
description of the quest, which I will talk more about later, and
the quest's Brain/Brawn ratings, in percentages.  A quest with, say
90% Brawn rating and 10% Brain suggests that it is a quest full
of combat, or has just a little combat which is exceptionally
difficult.  A quest with 10% Brawn and 90% Brain ratings, on the
other hand, encourages you to find solutions other than killing
in order to get things done, i.e. it requires you
to use that gray matter between your ears, and I don't mean earwax.
The quest that you are about to undertake is rated at 50% Brain
and 50% Brawn, so it will be a nice balance between the two.  Of
course, the combat part will be scaled down so that you, as a newbie,
can handle it, so don't let the large Brawn rating scare you off.
Similarly, though, don't let a quest's small Brawn rating make
you think that you can easily handle whatever combat that might come
along in the process of working on it; this is not always the case,
especially if you are of particularly low level.
     This leads us to a discussion about the rules behind questing.
You should type 'help quests' at the earliest opportunity and absorb
the information there.  Note especially the provision again sharing
'quest info' that is anything you have learned about a quest, including
but not limited to its location, the difficulty of the creatures
there in combat, the workings of a particular device within the
area, and anything else really that can be associated with the quest.
The exception, and an important one, is when you are partying
during a quest.  Then, while the party is questing, the members
should feel free to exchange information.  In fact, the whole
questing process becomes much easier if you do.  After all, two
heads are better than one (unless you're an ettin and both of
them are unbelievably stupid -- no offense to any ettins reading
this).  What one person doesn't come up with another might, and
the quest can be completed much faster.  Once the party breaks
up, however, this privilege is immediately sacrificed.  Whatever
you gain on your own, or with others, after that is not to be
shared with your former quest-mate.  You can be severely punished
for any such dissemination of quest info, so please, for your own
sake, don't do it, and similarly, don't prod others into disseminating
quest info to you as this is just as bad if not worse.
     Well, enough jabber for the moment, let's proceed.  If you
haven't done this quest before (in this character if you once
had another character which has since been wiped) please go
through the northern archway so we can get you some quest points!
